liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Yes vote advocate Thomas Mayo says he is positive the outcome of the vote will be yes. "We have well over 40,000 volunteers on the polling booths across the country for the pre-polls and we are hearing positive feedback of people coming through and saying they will vote yes. "Of course there is a mixture but the feeling is overall really positive. Mr Mayo says despite the polls pointing to a no vote, he hasn't lost hope. "I am optimistic. It is a different feeling on the ground. I have been leafleting and train stations and I have been door knocking and phone banking for a long time," he said speaking on ABC News Breakfast. "There is a different story out there and I hope that comes to a happy conclusion, where we recognise Indigenous people as we should have done long ago and we enshrine the ability for us to be heard," he says. "That is the key to closing the gap in life expectancy which in remote communities is something like 20 years difference, broadly it is around eight years, but we need to do better and I think that a yes vote gives us that opportunity. A no vote is just more of the same." When asked how how many Australians are undecided and will potentially make their decisions at the polling booths, Mr Mayo says: "it is around 30 per cent and that is matched by our experience on the doors and in the phone banking. "These final conversations in these last eight days are going to be vital." Mr Mayo says SA and Tasmania are swing states to focus on but it is important to think about all Australians. "As a campaign, we have made sure that we are spreading the word about what a hopeful and important step this will be for our nation. We are hoping that we can get six out of six."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Yes campaigner Thomas Mayo is 'optimistic' despite polls pointing to a No vote

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Tavleen Singh Rapper Briggs's Yes concert, named Now and Forever kicks off today in Shepparton, Victoria. The activist group A.B. Original released a song titled Yes, delivering an impassioned endorsement of a Yes vote in the referendum on an Indigenous Voice to Parliament. The track featuring Indigenous rapper Briggs, has gone off with over 4 million hits already. "I think that it speaks to that generation," says Briggs on the popularity of the song. "I reckon this is how people are talking in the pubs and in the lounge rooms." An impressive line-up of artists including Paul Kelly, Jimmy Barnes and Hilltop Hoods will be performing at Shepparton today, hoping to inform more people about the Voice referendum. Organised by Briggs, the day-long Yes concert is aimed at undecided voters. "Over the last few weeks, I was just wanting to put more positive stuff into the sphere, because it was like, so much vitriol and so negative," Briggs tells ABC News Breakfast. "And I think that the best way that we can show people what a Yes might look like is by putting a show together with artists that share the same kind of vision for unity and solidarity." Victoria has been inundated with heavy rains this week but the rapper and activist is hopeful the rain will hold off today. Can't make it to the gig? Luckily, there's a First and Forever Special streaming now on iview, showcasing live music highlights from Baker Boy, Briggs & many more.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Brent oil futures fell below US$85/bbl overnight, taking the total fall to 13% since the September peak. What's going on, you ask? Well, markets are now worried about the demand for oil. The US Energy Information Administration this week released data that showed US gasoline demand has fallen to the lowest level since 1998. And markets think that's because the price of oil and gasoline has been so high. In an analyst note, CBA's commodity expert Vivek Dhar explains markets were already on edge for any evidence of weak oil demand. "With the US now expected to face high interest rates for longer, particularly in the wake of the FOMC meeting in September, the fall in US gasoline demand last week amplified concerns that US fuel demand could weaken further over the coming year." A higher US dollar will also increase the cost of fuel in local currency terms, which could lead to demand concerns in developing countries. At the same time, there are also supply cuts coming from the oil cartel OPEC. Interesting times.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Oil prices continue to tumble

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia is the equal fifth most targeted nation in the Asia Pacific region when it comes to cyber attacks, according to Microsoft. The tech giant has released its annual Digital Defence Report, which covers how the security landscape has evolved in the past year. Microsoft's Mark Anderson says 'soft targets' like think tanks, NGOs and universities remain the top targets. "Threat actors likely view them as easier initial access vectors to gain insights into a country's policy or science and technology communities," he said. The US, Ukraine and Israel continue to be the most heavily attacked countries globally. Microsoft says organisations involved in policy making and execution were among the most targeted.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Microsoft says Australia has 5% of total cyber attacks in APAC region
